    "## **7. Model Training**\n",
    "\n",
    "We train four classifiers across the two tasks. Each model was selected based on its suitability for high-dimensional, sparse text data — the typical output of TF-IDF vectorisation. Below we document the rationale behind each modelling decision in detail.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### 7a. Binary Classification Models\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Logistic Regression\n",
    "\n",
    "Logistic Regression is the natural baseline for binary text classification. It models the log-odds of the positive class as a linear combination of the input features, making it highly interpretable — the learned coefficients directly indicate which words push a prediction toward positive or negative sentiment. A large positive coefficient on a word like `\"love\"` and a large negative coefficient on `\"crash\"` would be exactly the kind of signal a brand team could act on.\n",
    "\n",
    "For sparse TF-IDF matrices, Logistic Regression is computationally efficient and frequently competitive with far more complex models. We use the `lbfgs` solver, which is well-suited to this problem size and converges reliably. The regularisation parameter `C=1.0` applies moderate L2 regularisation to prevent the model from overfitting to high-frequency terms that appear predominantly in the training set.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Multinomial Naive Bayes\n",
    "\n",
    "Naive Bayes is a probabilistic classifier that models the likelihood of each word given a class label, and predicts the class with the highest posterior probability. It is called \"naive\" because it assumes all features (words) are conditionally independent given the class — an assumption that is clearly violated in natural language, but which nevertheless produces strong results in practice on text classification tasks.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Multinomial variant is specifically designed for count-based or frequency-based features, making it a natural fit for TF-IDF vectors. Its key advantages are speed and robustness to class imbalance — because Naive Bayes is a generative model that estimates class-conditional word probabilities, its predictions are less sensitive to skewed class frequencies than discriminative models like Logistic Regression.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### 7b. Multiclass Classification Models\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Random Forest\n",
    "\n",
    "Random Forest is an ensemble method that trains a large number of decision trees on random subsets of the training data and features, then aggregates their predictions by majority vote. This bagging strategy reduces variance and makes the model robust to overfitting — a significant advantage given the noise inherent in tweet text, where the same sentiment can be expressed in many different ways.\n",
    "\n",
    "For text classification, Random Forest has the additional advantage of capturing non-linear relationships between features. While TF-IDF features are individually interpretable, their interactions — for example, the co-occurrence of certain words — can carry predictive signal that a linear model cannot capture. We use 100 trees with a maximum depth of 10 to balance expressiveness with training efficiency. Random Forest also provides feature importance scores that give insight into which linguistic features drive predictions most strongly.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Linear SVM\n",
    "\n",
    "Support Vector Machines with a linear kernel are widely regarded as one of the strongest out-of-the-box models for high-dimensional text classification. The model works by finding the hyperplane in the TF-IDF feature space that maximally separates the classes — in practice, this corresponds to identifying the linear combination of word features that best discriminates between sentiment classes with the largest possible margin.\n",
    "\n",
    "`LinearSVC` is used rather than the kernel SVM (`SVC`) because it is specifically optimised for large, sparse matrices and trains significantly faster while achieving comparable accuracy. It is particularly effective in the regime we are operating in: many features (vocabulary size 5,000) relative to training examples, which is the characteristic structure of TF-IDF text classification problems."
   ]
  },
