   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## **12. Conclusions & Business Recommendations**\n",
    "\n",
    "### **Summary of Key Findings**\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Sentiment Distribution** — the dataset is heavily skewed toward Positive and Neutral sentiment, with Negative tweets representing only ~6% of all labelled examples. This imbalance is a defining challenge of the modelling task and directly informed our choice of F1 score over accuracy as the primary evaluation metric.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **Model Performance** — both success criteria were met:\n",
    "   - Binary classification (Positive vs. Negative): F1 score of **0.81** using Naive Bayes (best binary model)\n",
    "   - Multiclass classification (Positive / Neutral / Negative): Weighted F1 of **0.67** using SVM (best multiclass model)\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **Most Challenging Class** — Negative sentiment detection was the hardest task across all four models. In binary classification, both Logistic Regression and Naive Bayes achieved Negative class F1 scores of only **0.20–0.22**, despite high overall accuracy — a direct consequence of the severe class imbalance (only 114 negative examples in the test set vs. 596 positive). In multiclass classification, Random Forest failed entirely on the Negative class (F1: 0.00), while SVM managed a Negative class F1 of **0.37**. This confirms that the minority class is where the most work remains.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. **Key Insight — Accuracy is Misleading Here** — Logistic Regression and Naive Bayes both report ~86% accuracy, but their Negative class recall is only 11–12%. This means they are correctly identifying almost no negative tweets. The weighted F1 score exposes this, which is exactly why we selected it as our primary metric rather than accuracy.\n",
    "\n",
    "5. **Best Models by Task:**\n",
    "   - **Binary:** Naive Bayes (F1: 0.8086) narrowly outperforms Logistic Regression (F1: 0.8058)\n",
    "   - **Multiclass:** SVM (F1: 0.6726) substantially outperforms Random Forest (F1: 0.4731)\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### **Business Recommendations**\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **For Marketing Teams**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Recommendation | Rationale | Expected Impact |\n",
    "|----------------|-----------|-----------------| \n",
    "| Track positive word frequency | Words like `\"love\"`, `\"great\"`, `\"awesome\"` are strong predictors of positive sentiment | Early indicator of campaign success |\n",
    "| Monitor sentiment before and after product launches | Compare sentiment trends across time windows | Quantify the impact of product announcements |\n",
    "| Identify brand advocates | Users who consistently post positive tweets | Build a structured ambassador programme |\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **For Product Teams**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Recommendation | Rationale | Expected Impact |\n",
    "|----------------|-----------|-----------------| \n",
    "| Prioritise issues mentioned in negative tweets | Words like `\"crash\"`, `\"battery\"`, `\"slow\"` appear frequently in negative tweets | Address the most common complaints first |\n",
    "| Use language from positive tweets in product copy | Customer language resonates with prospects | Improve marketing and product descriptions |\n",
    "| Track feature requests embedded in neutral tweets | Neutral tweets often contain suggestions and observations | Inform the product roadmap |\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **For Customer Support**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Recommendation | Rationale | Expected Impact |\n",
    "|----------------|-----------|-----------------| \n",
    "| Do not fully automate negative tweet routing yet | With Negative class recall of only 11–28%, the models miss the majority of negative tweets | Human review remains essential for complaint detection |\n",
    "| Use SVM multiclass model for triage | SVM correctly identifies 28% of negative tweets — far better than Random Forest's 0% | Better than no filter, but thresholds should be set conservatively |\n",
    "| Prioritise longer negative tweets | Longer tweets tend to contain more detailed problem descriptions | More efficient use of support resources |\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### **Technical Recommendations**\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Deploy SVM for multiclass classification** — it is the clear winner on the three-class task and handles the class imbalance significantly better than Random Forest\n",
    "2. **Address class imbalance directly** — apply SMOTE oversampling or class-weight adjustments before retraining; the current Negative class performance (recall: 11–28%) is not production-ready\n",
    "3. **Retrain at least monthly** to capture new language patterns, product names, and evolving slang\n",
    "4. **Add emoji sentiment mapping** rather than removing emojis during cleaning — emojis are strong sentiment signals in tweet data\n",
    "5. **Implement confidence thresholding** — given the low Negative class recall, flag low-confidence predictions for human review rather than automating all decisions\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### **Future Work**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Direction | Description | Priority |\n",
    "|-----------|-------------|----------|\n",
    "| Transformer models | BERT or RoBERTa would handle class imbalance and negation far better than TF-IDF models | High |\n",
    "| Class imbalance handling | SMOTE, class weights, or cost-sensitive learning to improve Negative class recall | High |\n",
    "| Real-time pipeline | Connect to the Twitter/X API for live sentiment monitoring during events | High |\n",
    "| Interactive dashboard | Build a Tableau or Streamlit dashboard for non-technical stakeholders | Medium |\n",
    "| Aspect-based sentiment | Identify sentiment toward specific product features rather than the brand as a whole | Low |\n",
    "\n",
